{
  "text": "Coadhesion of P. gingivalis and S. gordonii is reasonably well characterized at the molecular level and involves cell surface proteins on both partners [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . These molecules include the 44-kDa fimbrillin subunit (FimA) and a 35-kDa outer membrane protein of P. gingivalis [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and the streptococcal antigen I/II polypeptides SspA (1,528 aa residues) and SspB (1,448 aa residues) [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Expression of SspB on the surface of Enterococcus faecalis cells confers on these cells the ability to bind P. gingivalis [CITATION_8] . Purified recombinant SspA or SspB polypeptide of S. gordonii binds P. gingivalis, whereas recombinant PAc (antigen I/II) from S. mutans does not (5). The P. gingivalis binding domain of SspB is defined by amino acid residues 1167 to 1250 [CITATION_9] and is identical in SspA [CITATION_10] . By contrast, this region within the S. mutans antigen I/II polypeptide differs in primary sequence and in predicted secondary structure [CITATION_11] .",
